1. Introduction

In this work, we create BGC class-specific models to predict the abundance of BGC classes in metagenomic samples. These models use the class abundance as the response variables, and the domains abundance of the corresponding classes, as the predictor variables. To train and evaluate the models, the data is randomly split (within the functions) to create the training and testing data sets.

We use four functions:

1. binary_model_fun: Trains and tests a binary classification model to predict the presence of BGC classes.
2. regression_model_fun: Trains and tests a regression model to predict the abundance of BGC classes.
3. double_model_fun: Integrates the previous two models. It creates a binary model based on the complete data set and a regression model using only the non-zero abundance rows of the response variables. Briefly, this function applies the binary model to identify samples where a class is present, and subsequently applies the regression model on this subset of samples to predict their abundance.
4. iter_model_fun: This function iteratively runs the double_model_fun to evaluate its performance by randomly generating in each iteration different training and testing data sets.

Load libraries, functions, and data
library(randomForest)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(vegan)
library(miscTools)
library(e1071)
source("toolbox.R")

TBL_DOM <- read.table("../data/138prkrich_domain_abund.csv", header=T, sep=",", row.names = 1)
TBL_CLASS <- read.table("../data/138prkrich_class_abund.csv", header=T, sep=",", row.names = 1)
TBL_CLASS2DOM <- read.table("../data/class2domain.csv", header=T, sep=",", row.names = 1)
Transform and join tables
TBL_DOM.trans <- decostand(TBL_DOM, method = "hellinger")
TBL_CLASS.trans <- decostand(TBL_CLASS, method = "hellinger")


data <- left_join(x = tibble::rownames_to_column(TBL_DOM.trans),
                  y = tibble::rownames_to_column(TBL_CLASS.trans), 
                  by = "rowname" )
Select bgc classes
bgc_classes <- c("nrps","terpene","t1pks","t3pks","ectoine","bacteriocin")

2. Linear Regression Models

Run the regression_model_fun using lm
lm_abund <- regression_model_fun(bgc = bgc_classes, 
                                 data = data,
                                 regression_method = "lm",
                                 class2dom = TBL_CLASS2DOM
                                 )
Visualize output
lapply(lm_abund,"[", 1:3 ) %>% 
       do.call("rbind", .)
##             cor       cor.pvalue   mse        
## nrps        0.3180063 0.04274436   0.03488361 
## terpene     0.6040457 2.893947e-05 0.0188501  
## t1pks       0.128541  0.4231657    0.01997138 
## t3pks       0.5264142 0.000407232  0.01233701 
## ectoine     0.6423132 5.978225e-06 0.009820759
## bacteriocin 0.5471942 0.0002137017 0.01630558
x <- lapply(lm_abund,"[[", 5) %>% 
      plyr::ldply(., data.frame)

ggplot(x, aes(x = resp, y=pred)) +
       geom_point() +
       facet_wrap( ~ .id, ncol = 2, nrow = 3, scales = "free" ) +
       xlab("response test") +
       ylab("predicted")

5. Evaluate Random Forest Binary Classification + Regression Models

Run the iter_model_fun with 100 iterations

drf_abund_iter <- iter_model_fun(bgc = bgc_classes, 
                                 data = data,
                                 binary_method = "rf",
                                 regression_method = "rf",
                                 iter= 100,
                                 class2dom = TBL_CLASS2DOM
                                )
Visualize output: correlation distributions
f <- function(x) lapply(x, "[[", "cor") %>% do.call("rbind", .) 
cors <- lapply(drf_abund_iter, f ) %>%
               plyr::ldply(., data.frame)


ggplot(cors, aes(cor)) +
       geom_histogram(bins = 20) +
       facet_wrap( ~ .id, ncol = 2, nrow = 3, scales = "free") +
       xlab("correlation") +
       xlim(c(-0.2,1))

Visualize output: MSE distributions
f <- function(x) lapply(x, "[[", "mse") %>% do.call("rbind", .)
mses <- lapply(drf_abund_iter, f ) %>%
               plyr::ldply(., data.frame)
  
ggplot(mses, aes(X..i..)) +
       geom_histogram(bins = 20) +
       facet_wrap( ~ .id, ncol = 2, nrow = 3, scales = "free") +
       xlab("mse") +
       xlim(c(0,0.075))
